ğŸ”¹ 1. Power-On Self-Test (POST): Checks CPU, RAM, video, BIOS. Errors? Look for beep codes (check docs) or black screen (video/RAM failure).
ğŸ”” Beep Codes: Hardware errors (e.g., CPU, GPU)â€”varies by BIOS maker.
ğŸ•’ 2. BIOS Battery and Time Errors: CMOS battery keeps settings/time. Replace CR2032 if "BIOS time incorrect" appears.
âš™ï¸ 3. BIOS Boot Order Configuration: Set priority (SSD > USB > Network). Change in BIOS if booting wrong.
ğŸŸ¦ 4. Windows Stop Errors (BSOD): Critical failureâ€”note stop code (e.g., 0xC0000135), try Last Known Good or Safe Mode. Causes: Bad hardware/drivers.
ğŸ§© 5. Application Crashes and Error Codes: Document message, check Event Viewer/Reliability Monitor. Reinstall/update app.
ğŸ–¥ï¸ 6. Display and Black Screen Troubleshooting: Check cables, power, input source. Swap monitor; boot VGA mode if needed.
âš¡ 7. Power Problems: Test outlet/cable/PSU with multimeter. Fans spin but no boot? Motherboard/GPU issue.
ğŸ¢ 8. Sluggish System Performance: Monitor CPU/memory/disk in Task Manager. Update, defrag, check malware.
ğŸŒ¡ï¸ 9. Overheating and Cooling Systems: Clean fans, check temps with HWMonitor. Sources: CPU/GPU. Fixes: Thermal paste, airflow.
ğŸ’¥ 10. Smoke, Odors, or Electrical Failure: Unplug, inspect for burnt capacitors. Replace faulty parts.
âš« 11. Random Shutdowns or Power Loss: Check overheating, loose connections. Review Event Viewer.
